When creating a bulk write with a single update using a pipeline to update the document, along with the {{let}} option to specify variables for that pipeline, the result heavily depends on whether this bulk write is executed using {{Manager::executeBulkWrite}} or {{Server::executeBulkWrite}}.

Take the following code:
{code}
$document = [
    '_id' => new MongoDB\BSON\ObjectId(),
    'day' => new MongoDB\BSON\UTCDateTime(),
    'fuel' => 'diesel',
    'openingPrice' => null,
    'closingPrice' => 1.529,
    'lowestPrice' => [
        '_id' => new MongoDB\BSON\ObjectId(),
        'date' => new MongoDB\BSON\UTCDateTime(),
        'price' => 1.529,
    ],
    'highestPrice' => [
        '_id' => new MongoDB\BSON\ObjectId(),
        'date' => new MongoDB\BSON\UTCDateTime(),
        'price' => 1.529,
    ],
    'prices' => [
        [
            '_id' => new MongoDB\BSON\ObjectId(),
            'date' => new MongoDB\BSON\UTCDateTime(),
            'price' => 1.529,
        ],
    ],
    'weightedAveragePrice' => 1.529,
];

$bulk = new MongoDB\Driver\BulkWrite(['let' => ['testDocument' => $document]]);
$bulk->update(['_id' => 1], [['$set' => ['document' => '$$testDocument']]], ['upsert' => true]);
{code}

When running the bulk write through {{Manager::executeBulkWrite}}, it is run as expected. However, when using {{Server::executeBulkWrite}}, the command sent to the server does not contain the {{let}} option, causing the pipeline to fail, and the process to terminate abnormally:
{code}
Fatal error: Uncaught MongoDB\Driver\Exception\BulkWriteException: Invalid $set :: caused by :: Use of undefined variable: testDocument in /Users/alcaeus/Code/mongodb/mongo-php-driver/tests/server/server-executeBulkWrite-010.php:38
[...]
Termsig=6
{code}

Removing the {{let}} option from the bulk write predictably leads to the same error on updates (as the variable really isn't defined), but does not terminate with a segmentation fault.

